<subSubSection pageId="81" pageNumber="82" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="81.[612,975,1215,1242]" box="[612,975,1215,1242]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">
<heading box="[612,975,1215,1242]" centered="true" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" reason="2">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fallen" baseAuthorityYear="1815" box="[612,900,1215,1242]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Elaphropeza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ephippiata">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[612,900,1215,1242]" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Elaphropeza ephippiata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="81.[189,1399,1281,1554]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">
Members of this group are characterised by the following combination of characters: two male genitalic rod-shaped apodemes (ventral and ejaculatory) present (
<figureCitation box="[856,959,1316,1343]" captionStart="Figs 117-122" captionStartId="80.[189,241,1895,1921]" captionTargetBox="[208,1383,295,1828]" captionTargetId="figure@80.[189,1398,285,1854]" captionTargetPageId="80" captionText="Figs 117-122. Elaphropeza bicaudata (Melander, 1928). 117. antenna, ♂, lateral view. 118. cerci, lateral view. 119. epandrium and cerci, dorsal view. 120. left surstylus, lateral view. 121. ♀ ovipositor, lateral view. 122. hind femur and tibia, ♂, anterior view. Scale bar= 0.1 mm (after Shamshev &amp; Grootaert 2007)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3723730" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3723730/files/figure.png" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Fig. 119</figureCitation>
); phallus short; long upturned bristle just above fore coxa absent; abdominal tergites 4 and/or 5 with squamiform setae (rarely absent); abdominal glands present between tergites 4 and 5. Additionally, in species of this group the hind tibia bears usually 1-2 anterodorsal bristles (but with quite numerous exceptions) (
<figureCitation box="[1086,1187,1422,1449]" captionStart="Figs 117-122" captionStartId="80.[189,241,1895,1921]" captionTargetBox="[208,1383,295,1828]" captionTargetId="figure@80.[189,1398,285,1854]" captionTargetPageId="80" captionText="Figs 117-122. Elaphropeza bicaudata (Melander, 1928). 117. antenna, ♂, lateral view. 118. cerci, lateral view. 119. epandrium and cerci, dorsal view. 120. left surstylus, lateral view. 121. ♀ ovipositor, lateral view. 122. hind femur and tibia, ♂, anterior view. Scale bar= 0.1 mm (after Shamshev &amp; Grootaert 2007)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3723730" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3723730/files/figure.png" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Fig. 122</figureCitation>
), cerci are usually fused to form a single lobe (
<figureCitation box="[542,646,1458,1484]" captionStart="Figs 123-126" captionStartId="83.[189,241,1151,1177]" captionTargetBox="[205,1368,331,1098]" captionTargetId="figure@83.[189,1399,319,1110]" captionTargetPageId="83" captionText="Figs 123-126. Elaphropeza limosa Shamshev &amp; Grootaert, 2007, ♂. 123. antenna, lateral view. 124. right epandrial lamella, lateral view, 125. epandrium and cerci, dorsal view. 126. left surstylus, lateral view. (after Shamshev &amp; Grootaert 2007)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3723732" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3723732/files/figure.png" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Fig. 123</figureCitation>
) and the right surstylus is usually not prominent. In females, sclerites of abdominal segment 8 (
<figureCitation box="[591,690,1493,1519]" captionStart="Figs 117-122" captionStartId="80.[189,241,1895,1921]" captionTargetBox="[208,1383,295,1828]" captionTargetId="figure@80.[189,1398,285,1854]" captionTargetPageId="80" captionText="Figs 117-122. Elaphropeza bicaudata (Melander, 1928). 117. antenna, ♂, lateral view. 118. cerci, lateral view. 119. epandrium and cerci, dorsal view. 120. left surstylus, lateral view. 121. ♀ ovipositor, lateral view. 122. hind femur and tibia, ♂, anterior view. Scale bar= 0.1 mm (after Shamshev &amp; Grootaert 2007)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3723730" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3723730/files/figure.png" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Fig. 121</figureCitation>
) are separated (except in 
<taxonomicName authority="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev, 2012" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev" authorityYear="2012" box="[991,1127,1493,1519]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Elaphropeza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="feminata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[991,1127,1493,1519]" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">E. feminata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1133,1225,1494,1520]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
) and sternite 8 is folded apically.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
